"1130","1194":"1194","1095":"1095","1070":"1070","about 1209":"about 1209","1104":"1104","1245":"1245","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1209":"1209","1109":"1109","Wales, South Yorkshire, United Kingdom":"Wales, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Ci Tredegyr, Monmouthshire, Wales l-sant, Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a short form of the personal name <i>Adelhard</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’. Compare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Ifor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) relationship name from Old Scandinavian  <i>Ívarr</i>,  <i>Iwar</i>,  <i>Ivar</i> ‘yew-army’. (ii) relationship name, possibly from the Welsh male given name  <i>Ifor</i>; if so, it is not clear that it survives today."],"variants":[{"name":"Ivers","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó hÍomhair</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Íomhar</i>’, a Gaelic form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Ívarr</i> (see   Iverson   2), with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. It is occasionally Anglicized as   Howard  . Also a shortened form of <b>Mac Íomhair</b> ‘son of <i>Íomhar</i>’, with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. See   McIver  .","North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ivar</i> (see   Iversen  ).","English: variant of <b>Iver</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, a habitational name from Iver (Buckinghamshire) named from Old English <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place called with the same word."]},{"name":"Iver","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Iver (Bucks) named from Old English * <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place named with the same word.","2  Scottish: (i) relationship name, reduced form of Irish and Scottish Gaelic  <b>Mac Íomhair</b>,  see  McIvor  . (ii) relationship name from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Ivar</i>;  see  Ivor  ."]},{"name":"Iverson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Iver, Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Selmer, Thor, Evald, Gunner, Helmer, Ingman, Jarl, Joneen.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Iversen   and of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b> (see   Ivarson  ), all cognates of 2 below.","English (Kent and London): patronymic from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, <i>Iwar</i>, <i>Ivar</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. Alternatively, the name might be a patronymic from the Welsh male personal name <i>Ifor</i>, itself from British Celtic <i>Iūdomāros</i> ‘lord’ + ‘great’, but if so, it is not clear that it survives today."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Bledri ap Ifor was born in Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales as the son of Ifor ap Bledri and Clydwen Ferch Gruffudd. He had at least 2 sons with Lleucu verch Gruffudd."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1095–1194":"1095–1194","1104–1130":"1104–1130","1109–Male":"1109–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1168–Female":"1168–Surnud","1209–1285":"1209–1285","1220–1245":"1220–1245","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1209–Male":"1209–Surnud","1065–Male":"1065–Surnud","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","1220":"1220","1065":"1065","1285":"1285","1130":"1130","1194":"1194","1095":"1095","1070":"1070","about 1209":"umbes 1209","1104":"1104","1245":"1245","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1209":"1209","1109":"1109","Wales, South Yorksh